England, United Kingdom":"Bulmer, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lamarsh, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Lamarsh, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Lamarsh, Essex, England":"Lamarsh, Essex, England"},"en":{"1553–1589":"1553–1589","1555–1612":"1555–1612","1572–1634":"1572–1634","1581–1656":"1581–1656","1572":"1572","1571":"1571","1581":"1581","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1656":"1656","1634":"1634","1612":"1612","17 Apr 1572":"17 April 1572","1589":"1589","1555":"1555","1587":"1587","1553":"1553","1585":"1585","about 1581":"about 1581","Bicton, Devon, England":"Bicton, Devon, England","Bulmer, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Bulmer, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Lamarsh, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Lamarsh, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Lamarsh, Essex, England":"Lamarsh, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Salmon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and French: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Salmon</i>, <i>Saumon</i>, a shortened form of <i>Salomon</i> (see   Solomon  ). The Normans introduced it to England, and it was current as a personal name there until at least the end of the 14th century. The derived surname is found throughout 13th- and 14th-century England, mostly in the spellings <i>Saleman</i> and <i>Salman</i>, which eventually became regularized as <i>Salmon</i>. See also 2 below, compare   Salman   3.","English: occasionally perhaps a nickname for someone ‘as wise as Solomon’. In Chaucer's <i>Canon's Yeoman's Tale</i>, it is stated: ‘And whan we been togidres euerichoon, Euery man semeth a Salomon’. King   Solomon   was famed for his wisdom.","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French, Middle English <i>salmon</i>, <i>saumo(u)n</i>, <i>saumun</i>, <i>samoun</i> ‘salmon’, no doubt given to someone who caught, sold, or ate the fish."],"variants":[{"name":"Sammon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan.","English and Irish (Mayo): variant of   Salmon  ."]},{"name":"Salmen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Wilhelm, Ilse.","English (Middlesex) and German: variant of English   Salmon   or Swiss German   Salman  ."]},{"name":"Salmons","meanings":["English: variant of   Salmon  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Salmond","meanings":["Scottish (Angus and Fife) and English: variant of   Salmon   1, with excrescent <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Salman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammad, Salman, Faisal, Ahmad, Amira, Imad, Issam, Khalid, Mohamed, Mohammed, Moosa, Omar.","Muslim: from a personal name based on Arabic <i>salmān</i> ‘safe’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Salmon   5."]},{"name":"Solomon","meanings":["Jewish, English, Scottish, Dutch, Swedish, French, Portuguese, Romanian, Ethiopian, and Eritrean; Spanish (<b>Solomón</b>): from a vernacular form of the Biblical Hebrew personal name <i>Shelomo</i>, a derivative of <i>shalom</i> ‘peace’. The name <i>Solomon</i> has for generations been a popular Jewish name and was also fairly widespread in the Middle Ages among Christians. In the Bible it is the name of King David's successor, noted for his wisdom; among Christians it was therefore also used as a nickname for a man who was considered wise. The spelling <i>Solomon</i> is used in the King James Bible of 1611, which is why this is the standard form of the name in modern English, but spellings with <i>Sal-</i> were more usual across continental Europe, the 1534 Lutheran Bible rendering it as <i>Salomo</i> and the 1560 Geneva Bible as   Salomon  . From the 7th century the spelling <i>Salomon</i> is recorded as a Christian personal name in France, where it was the name of several saints including a Breton king martyred in 874. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages (see   Salomon  ,   Salamon  ). See also   Salmon   1. — Note: Since Ethiopians and Eritreans do not have hereditary surnames, the Ethiopian and Eritrean name was registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]},{"name":"Zalman","meanings":["Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Salmon   5."]},{"name":"Salkin","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Salkin</i>, probably a pet form (with the Flemish and Middle English diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>) of <i>Salomon</i> (see   Salmon   and   Solomon  ).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the Yiddish personal name <i>Zalkind</i>, derived from   Salomon  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705202,"age":5,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":16,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":18,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":32,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":34,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Salmon was born in 1553, in Lamarsh, Essex, England. She married Joseph Underwood on 17 April 1572, in Bulmer, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in 1589, in Lamarsh, Essex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 36."},"et":{"1553–1589":"1553–1589","1555–1612":"1555–1612","1572–1634":"1572–1634","1581–1656":"1581–1656","1572":"1572","1571":"1571","1581":"1